Justification:
The Fifth OGP National Action Plan includes a specific action for the pubblication of open data (in open and machine-readable format) about the public tenders, where the civil society is fully engaged (see https://open.gov.it/sites/default/files/media/documents/2022-03/5nap-piano-azione-governo-aperto-italia.pdf).

RESPONSE TO THE REVIEWER
The action includes the following steps:
- reconnaissance of currently existing data sources that can complement that of ANAC (the anti-corruption authority) on public tenders to best cover the information needs of civil society;
- Integration of ANAC data with other data sources - e.g.: OpenCUP (that makes available data, in open format, on public investment decisions financed with national, community or regional public funds or private resources registered with the Unique Project Code), OpenCoesione (open government initiative on cohesion policies in Italy with the aim of promoting the effectiveness of interventions through the publication of data on funded projects and widespread civic participation.);  possibility of synergies with the "participation" action and civic debate. 
This action will be in charge of civil society organizations and aims to make the results of empowerment concrete: ANAC will play the role of the facilitator;
- collection of feedback, suggestions for improvement of data portals;
- Updating or extending the semantic content published;
- publication of APIs.

The action also includes the integration of data 
coming from civic monitoring (i.e. citizen-generated data) on projects receiving support from public resources. Civic monitoring means collecting data, evidence, information, news, interviewing actors involved in the design and implementation of interventions, visiting places and construction sites, fostering transparency and collaboration, and making proposals.

Improving metadata and data quality;
Implementing the arrangements set out in the Open Data Directive and in the HVD Regulation
